```

I'm confused why this would return `true` when there are no channels?

Previously, the function returned either a channel object, or `undefined`. (see [`Array.find`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/find) docs.)

The existing logic would handle the case where `state.core.channels.list` is an empty array because calling `find` on `[]` will always return `undefined`. So it sounds like possibly the problem was that `state.core.channels.list` was undefined? If that was the case, we could do something like

```javascript
// if no channels to match against, return true
if (state.core.channels.list === undefined) {
  return undefined;
}
```

But that would still return the opposite of what's here - `undefined` instead of `true`...

the `async def` is what makes it a coroutine which is in-turn what allows you to call `await token._wait_for_first(...)`.

The `await` is what yields execution to other processes allow them to continue execution while this function would normally block.

@gsalgado can probably correct me if I'm wrong here.

@ryanpetrello I am fine with `tz.gettz` being the default if you don't specify anything, but `tzinfos` can also be a callable, like this:

```python
def my_tzinfos(tzid):
    if tzid in SOME_LOOKUP_TABLE:
        return tzid[SOME_LOOKUP_TABLE]
    else:
        try:
            return dateutil.tz.tzstr(tzid)
        except ValueError:
            return tz.tzutc()
```

I don't really know if that particular function is something someone would actually want to do, but the point is that `tzinfos` is basically a mapping between `tzid` and a `tzinfo` object, so any function that provides `tzinfo` as a function of `tzid` should work. As a convenience, you can also provide a dictionary directly, rather than passing `mytzinfos.get`.

